Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Bulgaria. The Bulgarian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
The Bulgarian authorities have declared a national state of emergency until 13 April.
Borders and travel
The Bulgarian Government have announced severe restrictions on international travel, forbidding entry to British nationals from midnight 17/18 March, except for those with permanent or long term residence in Bulgaria, and closing the border with Turkey for passenger traffic.
The British Embassy Sofia is issuing regular updates on Facebook with the latest available information on departure options for British nationals wishing to leave Bulgaria.
Bansko
The ski resort of Bansko has been placed under quarantine until 1 April. British nationals have been given until 20 March to leave the town on official Ministry of Interior buses, which will only take those with flights booked directly to Sofia Airport. If youâ€™re in Bansko, you should, if necessary, rebook your flights for tomorrow and register at britishembassysofia@fco.gov.uk as soon as possible in order to get access to the buses which will leave tomorrow morning. British travellers remaining in Bansko beyond 20 March are likely to have to remain there until the end of the quarantine.
The British Embassy Sofia is issuing regular updates on Facebook with the latest available information on departure options for British nationals wishing to leave Bulgaria.
Local measures
Other measures include cancellation of cultural and sporting events; closure of shops, except food shops and pharmacies; closure of bars and restaurants; and closure of schools and universities; and a ban on groups of more than two adults congregating together
Further information
The Bulgarian Ministry of Health has published information (in Bulgarian) and has set up a hotline +359 2 807 87 57.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Bulgaria on the TravelHealthPro country page.
